132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 594
S.P. 278 In Senate, February 25, 2025
Resolve, Directing the State Auditor to Audit All State Agencies
Received by the Secretary of the Senate on February 19, 2025. Referred to the Committee
on State and Local Government pursuant to Joint Rule 308.2 and ordered printed.
DAREK M. GRANT
Secretary of the Senate
Presented by Senator BRADSTREET of Kennebec.
Cosponsored by Representative LIBBY of Auburn and
Representatives: CARUSO of Caratunk, CHAPMAN of Auburn, DRINKWATER of Milford,
FREDERICKS of Sanford, GREENWOOD of Wales, HENDERSON of Rumford,
SCHMERSAL-BURGESS of Mexico, UNDERWOOD of Presque Isle.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Sec. 1. State Auditor to audit all state agencies. Resolved: That the State
2 Auditor shall audit all state agencies and compile a report that lists for each state agency:
3 1. The number of current employees;
4 2. The number of newly hired employees over the last 5, 10, 15 and 20 years;
5 3. The current budget and the projected budget;
6 4. The growth of the budget over the last 5, 10, 15 and 20 years;
7 5. The agency's jurisdiction, roles and responsibilities;
8 6. The scope of current projects, completed projects and incomplete projects over the
9 last 5, 10, 15 and 20 years; and
10 7. The percentage of the total of the most current state biennial budget that the agency's
11 current budget represents.
12 Sec. 2. Report. Resolved: That the State Auditor shall submit the report under
13 section 1 to the joint standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over
14 appropriations and financial affairs no later than November 4, 2026.
15 SUMMARY
1166 This resolve requires the State Auditor to audit all state agencies and compile a report
1177 for each state agency listing the number of current employees; the number of newly hired
1188 employees over a period of time; the current and projected budget; the growth of the budget
1199 over a period of time; the agency's jurisdiction, roles and responsibilities; the scope of
2200 current, completed and incomplete projects over a period of time; and the percentage of the
2211 total of the most current state biennial budget the agency's budget represents.
